{"type":"message","id":"4ac52f23","parentId":"1e084cab","timestamp":"2026-03-25T03:07:25.013Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01Krjn8farXg5Cg7AyWTKuXU","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Fig. 1. Comparison of the frequency spectrum of real and generated samples in Case I.\r\n\r\nFig. 2. Comparison of the frequency spectrum of real and generated samples in Case II.\r\n\r\nFig. 3. Confusion matrices By SVM in Case I at various BRs for multiclass fault diagnosis. a:(upper left) 0.005. b:(upper right) 0.01. c:(lower left) 0.05. d:(lower right) 1.\r\n\r\nFig. 4. Confusion matrices By SVM in Case II at various BRs for multiclass fault diagnosis. a:(upper left) 0.005. b:(upper right) 0.01. c:(lower left) 0.05. d:(lower right) 1.\r\n\r\nFig. 5. Diagnostic accuracy of single-class imbalance fault diagnosis for Case I on (Left) data with class 0 as the minority class, (Right) data with class 5 as the minority class.\r\n\r\nFig. 6. Diagnostic accuracy of single-class imbalance fault diagnosis for Case II on (Left) data with class 1 as the minority class, (Right)data with class 3 as the minority class.\r\n\r\nFig. 7. Confusion matrices by SVM in Case I at various BRs for fault diagnosis with single class of class 5. a:(upper left) 0.05. b:(upper right) 0.1. c:(lower left) 0.5. d:(lower right) 1.\r\n\r\nFig. 8. Confusion matrices by SVM in Case II at various BRs for fault diagnosis with single class of class 3. a:(upper left) 0.05. b:(upper right) 0.1. c:(lower left) 0.5. d:(lower right).\r\n\r\nFig. 9. Result of multiclass diagnosis using SVM for Case I.\r\n\r\nFig. 10. Result of multiclass diagnosis using SVM for Case II.\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774408045013}}
