{"type":"message","id":"7bde1c5a","parentId":"1f7fb58f","timestamp":"2026-03-25T03:57:41.391Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Only those labels. So the numeric data is only in those tables we extracted.\n\nTherefore, we must fill the placeholders with numbers from these tables. The challenge is mapping to correct narrative spots.\n\nLet's look at the exact placeholder positions in experiments_p1.tex via grep:\n\nI'll extract lines with placeholders:","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_a1be8a7b0f0340f89d70fd3a","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -n '\\[X\\.XX\\]\\|\\[XX\\]\\|\\[XXX\\]\\|\\[XX\\.X\\%\\]' /home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-6/drafts/v3/experiments_p1.tex | sed 's/^/Line /'"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"stepfun/step-3.5-flash:free","usage":{"input":112254,"output":238,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":112492,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774411054614}}
{"type":"message","id":"41e0d25f","parentId":"7bde1c5a","timestamp":"2026-03-25T03:57:41.398Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_a1be8a7b0f0340f89d70fd3a","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Line 32:Additional competitive methods such as Support Vector Machines (SVM) \\cite{Cortes1995} and Random Forests (RF) \\cite{Breiman2001} are included to evaluate the framework's broad applicability across different classifier types. Table \\ref{tab:baselines} summarizes the architectural parameters and training configurations for these models to ensure a fair comparison. All deep learning models are implemented using the PyTorch framework and trained on an NVIDIA GeForce RTX GPU. We use the Adam optimizer \\cite{Kingma2015} with a learning rate of [X.XX] and a batch size of [XX]. To ensure convergence, the models are trained for [XXX] epochs, with the generator and discriminator updated in a 1:5 ratio as per the standard WGAN-GP guidelines. Specifically, for Case I, we compare our method against SMOTE \\cite{6}, baseline GAN implementations \\cite{1}, and specialized variants such as ICAC-CycleGAN-WGP \\cite{26} and CAC-CycleGAN-WGP \\cite{35}.\nLine 39:The quantitative evaluation of generation quality is presented in Table \\ref{tab:similarity}. Specifically, for Case I, the average PCC between real and fake samples reaches [X.XX], while the CS is approximately [X.XX]. These high scores indicate that the CAC-CycleGAN-WGP does not merely memorize the training data but learns the underlying manifold of the fault signatures. In comparison to standard GAN and ACGAN, our method demonstrates a significant improvement in spectral consistency, which can be attributed to the use of the gradient penalty and the Wasserstein loss that prevent mode collapse and provide a more informative training signal to the generator. The stability offered by the Wasserstein distance allows the generator to explore the data distribution more effectively, resulting in a wider diversity of generated samples that cover different parts of the fault signature space.\nLine 65:The computational efficiency of the framework is also a key consideration. While training a GAN can be computationally intensive—taking approximately [XX] minutes on the specified hardware for 500 epochs—the subsequent data generation is nearly instantaneous. A single forward pass through the generator can produce hundreds of samples in milliseconds. This decoupling of training and generation makes the CAC-CycleGAN-WGP an ideal candidate for real-time edge computing applications, where the generative model could be used to supplement online diagnostic streams on low-power devices."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":3,"aggregated":"Line 32:Additional competitive methods such as Support Vector Machines (SVM) \\cite{Cortes1995} and Random Forests (RF) \\cite{Breiman2001} are included to evaluate the framework's broad applicability across different classifier types. Table \\ref{tab:baselines} summarizes the architectural parameters and training configurations for these models to ensure a fair comparison. All deep learning models are implemented using the PyTorch framework and trained on an NVIDIA GeForce RTX GPU. We use the Adam optimizer \\cite{Kingma2015} with a learning rate of [X.XX] and a batch size of [XX]. To ensure convergence, the models are trained for [XXX] epochs, with the generator and discriminator updated in a 1:5 ratio as per the standard WGAN-GP guidelines. Specifically, for Case I, we compare our method against SMOTE \\cite{6}, baseline GAN implementations \\cite{1}, and specialized variants such as ICAC-CycleGAN-WGP \\cite{26} and CAC-CycleGAN-WGP \\cite{35}.\nLine 39:The quantitative evaluation of generation quality is presented in Table \\ref{tab:similarity}. Specifically, for Case I, the average PCC between real and fake samples reaches [X.XX], while the CS is approximately [X.XX]. These high scores indicate that the CAC-CycleGAN-WGP does not merely memorize the training data but learns the underlying manifold of the fault signatures. In comparison to standard GAN and ACGAN, our method demonstrates a significant improvement in spectral consistency, which can be attributed to the use of the gradient penalty and the Wasserstein loss that prevent mode collapse and provide a more informative training signal to the generator. The stability offered by the Wasserstein distance allows the generator to explore the data distribution more effectively, resulting in a wider diversity of generated samples that cover different parts of the fault signature space.\nLine 65:The computational efficiency of the framework is also a key consideration. While training a GAN can be computationally intensive—taking approximately [XX] minutes on the specified hardware for 500 epochs—the subsequent data generation is nearly instantaneous. A single forward pass through the generator can produce hundreds of samples in milliseconds. This decoupling of training and generation makes the CAC-CycleGAN-WGP an ideal candidate for real-time edge computing applications, where the generative model could be used to supplement online diagnostic streams on low-power devices.","cwd":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/leader/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774411061395}}
