{"type":"message","id":"695e39dd","parentId":"9472e0a7","timestamp":"2026-03-25T04:55:28.730Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"现在开始修复paper.tex。我需要一个新的、干净的paper.tex，可能要从头开始构建。但先修复现有的版本。让我读取v3的paper.tex以便修改。首先，修复引用格式问题。用户说“reference cite 格式不对，应该用普通的\\cite，确保编译后显示的是数字”。这可能意味着natbib的square样式`\\setcitestyle{square}`产生的引用格式是`[数字]`，而用户可能想要的是`[数字]`但也许目前的样式不对。实际上`square`样式产生的是`[数字]`，这是IEEE期刊常见的格式。但也许用户想要`数字`或者`[数字]`但当前可能显示为其他格式。让我检查一下引用在PDF中如何显示。但最简单的解决方法是使用标准的IEEEtran引用样式：移除natbib包，使用`\\bibliographystyle{IEEEtran}`。\n\n让我检查当前的头部：`\\usepackage{natbib}` 和 `\\setcitestyle{square}`。我将改为标准的IEEEtran引用：移除natbib行，并确保`\\bibliographystyle{IEEEtran}`。现在让我修改paper.tex。","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"019d2358f90aa6626d5ad903d6ca926e","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-6/final/v3/paper.tex","limit":20}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.2","usage":{"input":144554,"output":657,"cacheRead":128,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":145339,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774414494370}}
{"type":"message","id":"c50bcf3f","parentId":"695e39dd","timestamp":"2026-03-25T04:55:28.736Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"019d2358f90aa6626d5ad903d6ca926e","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\\documentclass[twocolumn]{IEEEtran}\n\\usepackage{graphicx}\n\\usepackage{amsmath}\n\\usepackage{amssymb}\n\\usepackage{booktabs}\n\\usepackage{multirow}\n\\usepackage{caption}\n\\usepackage{natbib}\n\\setcitestyle{square}\n\n\\begin{document}\n\n\\title{CAC-CycleGAN-WGP: Imbalanced Bearing Fault Diagnosis via Cross-Domain Signal Translation with Wasserstein Gradient Penalty}\n\\author{Anonymous Author(s)}\n\\maketitle\n\n\\begin{abstract}\nRolling element bearings are critical components in industrial machinery, and their failure can lead to catastrophic system breakdowns. While deep learning has significantly advanced fault diagnosis, the performance of these models is often hampered by the class imbalance problem, where fault samples are scarce compared to normal data. To address this challenge, this paper proposes a novel framework termed CAC-CycleGAN-WGP for imbalanced bearing fault diagnosis. The methodological core involves a CycleGAN architecture that transforms normal vibration signals into realistic fault signals, integrated with a Conditional Auxiliary Classifier (CAC) to accurately capture the marginal probability distributions of various fault categories. To ensure training stability and suppress mode collapse, we incorporate Wasserstein distance with a Gradient Penalty (WGP). Furthermore, a quality assessment method based on Stacked Autoencoders (SAE) is developed to evaluate the fidelity of the generated samples. Extensive experiments are conducted on two imbalanced bearing datasets: the Case Western Reserve University (CWRU) dataset and a custom laboratory dataset. Comparative results against state-of-the-art methods, including SMOTE, GAN, WGAN, ACGAN, and CAC-CycleGAN-WGP, demonstrate that the proposed CAC-CycleGAN-WGP significantly improves diagnostic accuracy and robustness under severe data imbalance, providing a viable solution for real-world industrial health monitoring.\n\\end{abstract}\n\n\n[478 more lines in file. Use offset=21 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774414528732}}
{"type":"message","id":"1445bb6d","parentId":"c50bcf3f","timestamp":"2026-03-25T04:56:39.584Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"首先，我将把头部改成标准的IEEEtran引用样式：移除`\\usepackage{natbib}`和`\\setcitestyle{square}`。然后确保使用`\\bibliographystyle{IEEEtran}`。让我编辑这个文件。使用edit工具。首先，移除natbib行。","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"019d235a05cc70ce36b0fbb77501f84e","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-6/final/v3/paper.tex","oldText":"\\documentclass[twocolumn]{IEEEtran}\n\\usepackage{graphicx}\n\\usepackage{amsmath}\n\\usepackage{amssymb}\n\\usepackage{booktabs}\n\\usepackage{multirow}\n\\usepackage{caption}\n\\usepackage{natbib}\n\\setcitestyle{square}","newText":"\\documentclass[twocolumn]{IEEEtran}\n\\usepackage{graphicx}\n\\usepackage{amsmath}\n\\usepackage{amssymb}\n\\usepackage{booktabs}\n\\usepackage{multirow}\n\\usepackage{caption}\n\\usepackage{flushend}\n\\usepackage{balance}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.2","usage":{"input":777,"output":343,"cacheRead":144640,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":145760,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774414528737}}
{"type":"message","id":"d7be4b5e","parentId":"1445bb6d","timestamp":"2026-03-25T04:56:39.595Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"019d235a05cc70ce36b0fbb77501f84e","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-6/final/v3/paper.tex."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n   4 \\usepackage{amssymb}\n   5 \\usepackage{booktabs}\n   6 \\usepackage{multirow}\n   7 \\usepackage{caption}\n-  8 \\usepackage{natbib}\n-  9 \\setcitestyle{square}\n+  8 \\usepackage{flushend}\n+  9 \\usepackage{balance}\n  10 \n  11 \\begin{document}\n  12 \n  13 \\title{CAC-CycleGAN-WGP: Imbalanced Bearing Fault Diagnosis via Cross-Domain Signal Translation with Wasserstein Gradient Penalty}\n     ...","firstChangedLine":8},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774414599591}}
{"type":"message","id":"9a569615","parentId":"d7be4b5e","timestamp":"2026-03-25T04:57:53.471Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"接下来，我需要确保`\\bibliographystyle{IEEEtran}`在`\\bibliography{references}`之前。让我搜索文件的结尾部分。","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"019d235b2f73378202e8880eaddca254","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"tail -50 /home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-6/final/v3/paper.tex"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.2","usage":{"input":329,"output":144,"cacheRead":145408,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":145881,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774414599595}}
{"type":"message","id":"857495aa","parentId":"9a569615","timestamp":"2026-03-25T04:57:53.481Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"019d235b2f73378202e8880eaddca254","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\\label{subsec:sensitivity}\n\nIn this final part of the experimental evaluation, we investigate the robustness of the proposed framework under varying operational constraints, specifically focusing on its sensitivity to the initial training sample size and the severity of the class imbalance. An ideal diagnostic system must maintain high performance even when the available labeled data for certain faults is extremely scarce, a condition frequently encountered in the early stages of industrial deployment or for catastrophic failures that rarely occur.\n\nFirst, we vary the number of real training samples available for the minority classes from 5\\% to 50\\% of the majority class size to test the limits of the data augmentation component. \\begin{figure}\n\\centering\n\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{fig10_part1.png}\n\\caption{Figure Sensitivity}\n\\label{fig:sensitivity}\n\\end{figure} shows the change in diagnostic accuracy as a function of this imbalance ratio. The results indicate that our method maintains an F1-score above 0.85 even when the imbalance ratio is as severe as 1:20 (5%). This robustness is attributed to the framework’s ability to extract deep latent features from fewer samples and expand them into a representative synthetic set. While performance naturally scales with the amount of real data, the rate of decline in our method is significantly flatter compared to traditional Oversampling (SMOTE) or standard GAN-based methods. This suggests that the WGAN-GP is less prone to \"overfitting\" on the small minority set, as the Wasserstein objective encourages a smoother transition across the feature space than the linear interpolation used in SMOTE.\n\nFurthermore, we evaluate the robustness of the Sparse Autoencoder (SAE) feature extractor used in our diagnostic pipeline against external environmental noise. \\begin{figure}\n\\centering\n\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{fig10_part2.png}\n\\caption{Figure Sae Error}\n\\label{fig:sae_error}\n\\end{figure} tracks the SAE reconstruction error variation across different noisy environments where the Signal-to-Noise Ratio (SNR) varies from -5dB to 20dB. The proposed model exhibits lower sensitivity to Gaussian noise injected into the input signals compared to traditional deep learning models. This is likely because the generative augmentation process itself acts as a form of data-centric regularization, teaching the model to ignore non-essential fluctuations and focus on the core structural components of the fault signal that are invariant to noise.\n\n\\begin{table}[htbp]\n\\centering\n\\caption{ROBUSTNESS TEST RESULTS}\n\\label{tab:robustness}\n\\begin{tabular}{cccccc}\n\\hline\nSpeed (RPM) & Load (Nm) & Accuracy & F1 & MMD & SAE Error \\\\\n\\hline\n800 & 0 & 92.1 & 0.89 & 0.012 & 0.085 \\\\\n800-1000 & 10 & 93.5 & 0.91 & 0.010 & 0.078 \\\\\n1500 & 20 & 91.8 & 0.88 & 0.014 & 0.092 \\\\\n\\hline\n\\end{tabular}\n\\end{table} provides the detailed results of these robustness tests across different operating speeds (800, 1200, and 1500 RPM) and loads (0, 10, and 20 Nm). The consistent performance across these varying conditions—with a total accuracy variance of less than 2.3\\%—suggests that the combination of WGAN-GP for distribution matching and the SAE for robust feature extraction creates a diagnostic system that is highly adaptable to the complexities of real-world industrial environments. The ability to handle varying degrees of data scarcity, environmental noise, and varying load conditions makes this framework a reliable and practical solution for automated fault diagnosis in critical machinery where \"perfect\" data is rarely available. The stability of the SAE reconstruction error specifically proves that the learned features remain invariant to operational shifts, which is a key requirement for deployment in variable-speed industrial processes.\n\n\n\\section{Conclusion}\n\\label{sec:conclusion}\n\n\\subsection{Summary}\nIn this research, we have developed a novel data augmentation framework, designated as the Conditional Auxiliary Classifier Cycle-consistent Generative Adversarial Network with Wasserstein Gradient Penalty (CAC-CycleGAN-WGP), to address the persistent challenges of imbalanced bearing fault diagnosis. The proposed architecture integrates a conditional auxiliary classifier to enhance class-conditional generation, while the inclusion of the Wasserstein distance with a gradient penalty (WGP) stabilizes the training mechanism and effectively mitigates the risks of gradient vanishing. Furthermore, we have introduced a Stacked Autoencoder (SAE)-based evaluation methodology to quantitatively assess the fidelity and diversity of the generated vibration samples. By mapping high-dimensional vibration signals into a compact and representative latent feature space, the SAE facilitates a more robust feature-level comparison between synthetic and real experimental data. This ensures that the generated minority class samples accurately represent the underlying physical fault characteristics, providing a solid foundation for robust diagnostic model training.\n\n\\subsection{Key Findings}\nComprehensive experimental evaluations conducted on various standard bearing fault datasets demonstrate the exceptional effectiveness of the CAC-CycleGAN-WGP framework. Our results indicate that the proposed methodology significantly alleviates the performance degradation typically caused by extreme data imbalance scenarios in industrial settings. Specifically, even when subjected to a challenging imbalance ratio of 1:20, the framework maintains an impressively high level of diagnostic accuracy, consistently achieving an F-1 score exceeding 0.85. This performance markedly outperforms five state-of-the-art baseline models, including traditional GAN configurations and various SMOTE-based variants. A critical finding is the framework's superior ability to prevent mode collapse through the synergy of the cycle-consistent loss function and the auxiliary classifier constraints. Detailed ablation studies further underscore the vital contribution of the CAC module, which independently accounts for an approximately 40\\% improvement in minority class classification accuracy. Additionally, the developed model exhibits remarkable noise robustness, maintaining high and stable diagnostic performance across a wide spectrum of Signal-to-Noise Ratios (SNR) ranging from -5~dB to 20~dB. Furthermore, across various experimental tests involving different rotational speeds and load conditions, the diagnostic precision variance remains consistently below 2.3\\%, underscoring the strong generalizability of the proposed approach.\n\n\\subsection{Future Work}\nWhile the CAC-CycleGAN-WGP framework has shown highly promising results in controlled environments, several critical avenues for future research remain. Subsequent efforts will focus on extending these augmentation capabilities to more complex non-stationary operating conditions where rotational speeds are time-varying, posing greater challenges for feature extraction and signal generation. Furthermore, we aim to investigate the framework's practical deployment in complex and harsh industrial settings characterized by multi-source interference and varying sensor locations. Integrating advanced domain adaptation techniques into the generative process could further enhance the transferability of the augmented data across different machines and sensor configurations. Finally, optimizing the computational efficiency of the training process to allow for real-time diagnostic model updates in edge computing devices remains a high priority for ensuring the practical, large-scale applicability of this technology within the evolving smart manufacturing and predictive maintenance ecosystems.\n\n\n\\bibliographystyle{IEEEtran}\n\\bibliography{references}\n\\end{document}"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":5,"aggregated":"\\label{subsec:sensitivity}\n\nIn this final part of the experimental evaluation, we investigate the robustness of the proposed framework under varying operational constraints, specifically focusing on its sensitivity to the initial training sample size and the severity of the class imbalance. An ideal diagnostic system must maintain high performance even when the available labeled data for certain faults is extremely scarce, a condition frequently encountered in the early stages of industrial deployment or for catastrophic failures that rarely occur.\n\nFirst, we vary the number of real training samples available for the minority classes from 5\\% to 50\\% of the majority class size to test the limits of the data augmentation component. \\begin{figure}\n\\centering\n\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{fig10_part1.png}\n\\caption{Figure Sensitivity}\n\\label{fig:sensitivity}\n\\end{figure} shows the change in diagnostic accuracy as a function of this imbalance ratio. The results indicate that our method maintains an F1-score above 0.85 even when the imbalance ratio is as severe as 1:20 (5%). This robustness is attributed to the framework’s ability to extract deep latent features from fewer samples and expand them into a representative synthetic set. While performance naturally scales with the amount of real data, the rate of decline in our method is significantly flatter compared to traditional Oversampling (SMOTE) or standard GAN-based methods. This suggests that the WGAN-GP is less prone to \"overfitting\" on the small minority set, as the Wasserstein objective encourages a smoother transition across the feature space than the linear interpolation used in SMOTE.\n\nFurthermore, we evaluate the robustness of the Sparse Autoencoder (SAE) feature extractor used in our diagnostic pipeline against external environmental noise. \\begin{figure}\n\\centering\n\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{fig10_part2.png}\n\\caption{Figure Sae Error}\n\\label{fig:sae_error}\n\\end{figure} tracks the SAE reconstruction error variation across different noisy environments where the Signal-to-Noise Ratio (SNR) varies from -5dB to 20dB. The proposed model exhibits lower sensitivity to Gaussian noise injected into the input signals compared to traditional deep learning models. This is likely because the generative augmentation process itself acts as a form of data-centric regularization, teaching the model to ignore non-essential fluctuations and focus on the core structural components of the fault signal that are invariant to noise.\n\n\\begin{table}[htbp]\n\\centering\n\\caption{ROBUSTNESS TEST RESULTS}\n\\label{tab:robustness}\n\\begin{tabular}{cccccc}\n\\hline\nSpeed (RPM) & Load (Nm) & Accuracy & F1 & MMD & SAE Error \\\\\n\\hline\n800 & 0 & 92.1 & 0.89 & 0.012 & 0.085 \\\\\n800-1000 & 10 & 93.5 & 0.91 & 0.010 & 0.078 \\\\\n1500 & 20 & 91.8 & 0.88 & 0.014 & 0.092 \\\\\n\\hline\n\\end{tabular}\n\\end{table} provides the detailed results of these robustness tests across different operating speeds (800, 1200, and 1500 RPM) and loads (0, 10, and 20 Nm). The consistent performance across these varying conditions—with a total accuracy variance of less than 2.3\\%—suggests that the combination of WGAN-GP for distribution matching and the SAE for robust feature extraction creates a diagnostic system that is highly adaptable to the complexities of real-world industrial environments. The ability to handle varying degrees of data scarcity, environmental noise, and varying load conditions makes this framework a reliable and practical solution for automated fault diagnosis in critical machinery where \"perfect\" data is rarely available. The stability of the SAE reconstruction error specifically proves that the learned features remain invariant to operational shifts, which is a key requirement for deployment in variable-speed industrial processes.\n\n\n\\section{Conclusion}\n\\label{sec:conclusion}\n\n\\subsection{Summary}\nIn this research, we have developed a novel data augmentation framework, designated as the Conditional Auxiliary Classifier Cycle-consistent Generative Adversarial Network with Wasserstein Gradient Penalty (CAC-CycleGAN-WGP), to address the persistent challenges of imbalanced bearing fault diagnosis. The proposed architecture integrates a conditional auxiliary classifier to enhance class-conditional generation, while the inclusion of the Wasserstein distance with a gradient penalty (WGP) stabilizes the training mechanism and effectively mitigates the risks of gradient vanishing. Furthermore, we have introduced a Stacked Autoencoder (SAE)-based evaluation methodology to quantitatively assess the fidelity and diversity of the generated vibration samples. By mapping high-dimensional vibration signals into a compact and representative latent feature space, the SAE facilitates a more robust feature-level comparison between synthetic and real experimental data. This ensures that the generated minority class samples accurately represent the underlying physical fault characteristics, providing a solid foundation for robust diagnostic model training.\n\n\\subsection{Key Findings}\nComprehensive experimental evaluations conducted on various standard bearing fault datasets demonstrate the exceptional effectiveness of the CAC-CycleGAN-WGP framework. Our results indicate that the proposed methodology significantly alleviates the performance degradation typically caused by extreme data imbalance scenarios in industrial settings. Specifically, even when subjected to a challenging imbalance ratio of 1:20, the framework maintains an impressively high level of diagnostic accuracy, consistently achieving an F-1 score exceeding 0.85. This performance markedly outperforms five state-of-the-art baseline models, including traditional GAN configurations and various SMOTE-based variants. A critical finding is the framework's superior ability to prevent mode collapse through the synergy of the cycle-consistent loss function and the auxiliary classifier constraints. Detailed ablation studies further underscore the vital contribution of the CAC module, which independently accounts for an approximately 40\\% improvement in minority class classification accuracy. Additionally, the developed model exhibits remarkable noise robustness, maintaining high and stable diagnostic performance across a wide spectrum of Signal-to-Noise Ratios (SNR) ranging from -5~dB to 20~dB. Furthermore, across various experimental tests involving different rotational speeds and load conditions, the diagnostic precision variance remains consistently below 2.3\\%, underscoring the strong generalizability of the proposed approach.\n\n\\subsection{Future Work}\nWhile the CAC-CycleGAN-WGP framework has shown highly promising results in controlled environments, several critical avenues for future research remain. Subsequent efforts will focus on extending these augmentation capabilities to more complex non-stationary operating conditions where rotational speeds are time-varying, posing greater challenges for feature extraction and signal generation. Furthermore, we aim to investigate the framework's practical deployment in complex and harsh industrial settings characterized by multi-source interference and varying sensor locations. Integrating advanced domain adaptation techniques into the generative process could further enhance the transferability of the augmented data across different machines and sensor configurations. Finally, optimizing the computational efficiency of the training process to allow for real-time diagnostic model updates in edge computing devices remains a high priority for ensuring the practical, large-scale applicability of this technology within the evolving smart manufacturing and predictive maintenance ecosystems.\n\n\n\\bibliographystyle{IEEEtran}\n\\bibliography{references}\n\\end{document}","cwd":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/leader/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774414673477}}
{"type":"message","id":"da8ea6a5","parentId":"857495aa","timestamp":"2026-03-25T04:58:17.450Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"很好，`\\bibliographystyle{IEEEtran}`已经存在。但是，我还需要检查是否在所有引用中使用了`\\cite{}`。现在我需要修复概念图的双栏显示问题。我需要找到`fig1.png`、`fig2.png`、`fig3.png`的位置，并将它们改为`figure*`环境。让我搜索一下包含这些图形的`\\begin{figure}`。","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"019d235b8bbd2c5563d50988babf5c05","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -B2 -A4 'fig2.png\\|fig3.png' /home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-6/final/v3/paper.tex"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.2","usage":{"input":113492,"output":276,"cacheRead":31936,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":145704,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774414673481}}
{"type":"message","id":"7bec73d5","parentId":"da8ea6a5","timestamp":"2026-03-25T04:58:17.459Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"019d235b8bbd2c5563d50988babf5c05","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The overall architecture of the CAC-CycleGAN-WGP framework is meticulously designed to transform imbalanced raw vibration signals into a balanced dataset by generating high-fidelity synthetic fault samples. As illustrated in \\begin{figure}\n\\centering\n\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{fig2.png}\n\\caption{Figure Architecture}\n\\label{fig:architecture}\n\\end{figure}, the system consists of five primary components: two generators ($G$ and $F$), two discriminators ($D_X$ and $D_Y$), an Auxiliary Classifier (AC), the Wasserstein Gradient Penalty (WGP) module, and a Sparse Autoencoder (SAE) based evaluator. This multi-component assembly ensures that the model can handle the complexities of different fault types, such as inner race, outer race, and ball defects, which often exhibit overlapping signal features in the time-frequency domain. In this context, we leverage the CycleGAN \\cite{4} framework for domain-to-domain mapping, combined with the stable training advantages of WGAN-GP \\cite{3} and the categorical guidance of ACGAN \\cite{5}.\n\n--\nThe SAE architecture, illustrated in \\begin{figure}\n\\centering\n\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{fig3.png}\n\\caption{Figure Sae}\n\\label{fig:sae}\n\\end{figure}, consists of multiple layers of sparse autoencoders stacked to form a deep representation learner. Each layer is pre-trained to minimize the reconstruction error of its input, progressively extracting high-level abstract features from the raw time-series or frequency-domain data. The encoding stage compresses the input into a latent bottleneck, while the decoding stage attempts to recreate the original signal from this reduced representation. During the evaluation phase, the SAE is trained exclusively on the real data from the target domain $Y$. The fundamental assumption is that if the generator $G$ successfully captures the underlying distribution of domain $Y$, the generated samples $\\tilde{y}$ should yield a reconstruction error comparable to that of real samples."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":4,"aggregated":"The overall architecture of the CAC-CycleGAN-WGP framework is meticulously designed to transform imbalanced raw vibration signals into a balanced dataset by generating high-fidelity synthetic fault samples. As illustrated in \\begin{figure}\n\\centering\n\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{fig2.png}\n\\caption{Figure Architecture}\n\\label{fig:architecture}\n\\end{figure}, the system consists of five primary components: two generators ($G$ and $F$), two discriminators ($D_X$ and $D_Y$), an Auxiliary Classifier (AC), the Wasserstein Gradient Penalty (WGP) module, and a Sparse Autoencoder (SAE) based evaluator. This multi-component assembly ensures that the model can handle the complexities of different fault types, such as inner race, outer race, and ball defects, which often exhibit overlapping signal features in the time-frequency domain. In this context, we leverage the CycleGAN \\cite{4} framework for domain-to-domain mapping, combined with the stable training advantages of WGAN-GP \\cite{3} and the categorical guidance of ACGAN \\cite{5}.\n\n--\nThe SAE architecture, illustrated in \\begin{figure}\n\\centering\n\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{fig3.png}\n\\caption{Figure Sae}\n\\label{fig:sae}\n\\end{figure}, consists of multiple layers of sparse autoencoders stacked to form a deep representation learner. Each layer is pre-trained to minimize the reconstruction error of its input, progressively extracting high-level abstract features from the raw time-series or frequency-domain data. The encoding stage compresses the input into a latent bottleneck, while the decoding stage attempts to recreate the original signal from this reduced representation. During the evaluation phase, the SAE is trained exclusively on the real data from the target domain $Y$. The fundamental assumption is that if the generator $G$ successfully captures the underlying distribution of domain $Y$, the generated samples $\\tilde{y}$ should yield a reconstruction error comparable to that of real samples.","cwd":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/leader/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774414697456}}
{"type":"message","id":"793b15ca","parentId":"7bec73d5","timestamp":"2026-03-25T04:58:52.266Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"我发现这些图形直接内联在句子中，格式是“As illustrated in \\begin{figure} ... \\end{figure},”。这是错误的。我需要将每个figure环境作为一个独立的块，放在句子的开头或单独一行。而且，fig1在哪里？没有找到fig1。也许它是“Figure 1”？让我搜索“Figure 1”。但首先，我需要修复这些figure环境。让我先修复fig2的figure环境。我将用`figure*`环境替换，并放在句子之前。找到并修复这些内联figure。我需要编辑paper.tex来纠正这个问题。让我在文档中找到`\\begin{figure}`的位置。我会将每个`\\begin{figure}`改为`\\begin{figure*}[htbp]`，并确保它们作为独立的环境。\n\n首先，让我找到所有figure环境的位置。使用sed或编辑整个文件。最直接的方法是写一个Python脚本来修复LaTeX。不过，手动编辑会更可靠。我将对每个figure进行编辑。\n\n首先，找到fig2的figure环境。让我看看其上下文：它出现在“As illustrated in \\begin{figure}...\\end{figure}, the system consists...”中。我需要将其改为：\n```\n\\begin{figure*}[htbp]\n\\centering\n\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{fig2.png}\n\\caption{Figure Architecture}\n\\label{fig:architecture}\n\\end{figure*}\n\nThe overall architecture of the CAC-CycleGAN-WGP framework...\n```\n\n但我必须小心，因为这段文本可能在figure环境之前就已经开始了。我将使用edit工具来修复fig2的环境。先获取旧文本。它很可能是一个多行的块。让我查看这个部分的确切内容，从“As illustrated in”开始。","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"019d235c13aee0ba1994f150557d0a52","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-6/final/v3/paper.tex","limit":15,"offset":70}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.2","usage":{"input":112887,"output":953,"cacheRead":31936,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":145776,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774414697460}}
{"type":"message","id":"530b64c8","parentId":"793b15ca","timestamp":"2026-03-25T04:58:52.273Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"019d235c13aee0ba1994f150557d0a52","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\\subsection{Overall Framework Architecture}\n\\label{subsec:framework}\n\nThe overall architecture of the CAC-CycleGAN-WGP framework is meticulously designed to transform imbalanced raw vibration signals into a balanced dataset by generating high-fidelity synthetic fault samples. As illustrated in \\begin{figure}\n\\centering\n\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{fig2.png}\n\\caption{Figure Architecture}\n\\label{fig:architecture}\n\\end{figure}, the system consists of five primary components: two generators ($G$ and $F$), two discriminators ($D_X$ and $D_Y$), an Auxiliary Classifier (AC), the Wasserstein Gradient Penalty (WGP) module, and a Sparse Autoencoder (SAE) based evaluator. This multi-component assembly ensures that the model can handle the complexities of different fault types, such as inner race, outer race, and ball defects, which often exhibit overlapping signal features in the time-frequency domain. In this context, we leverage the CycleGAN \\cite{4} framework for domain-to-domain mapping, combined with the stable training advantages of WGAN-GP \\cite{3} and the categorical guidance of ACGAN \\cite{5}.\n\nThe workflow begins with the input of raw vibration signals from both the majority class (normally functioning bearings) and the minority class (faulty bearings). Unlike standard GANs that map from a latent noise space to the data distribution—often resulting in a lack of structural coherence—our framework utilizes the CycleGAN structure to perform domain-to-domain translation. Generator $G$ is tasked with mapping samples from the normal domain $X$ to the fault domain $Y$, while generator $F$ performs the inverse mapping. This approach leverages the underlying structural similarities between normal and faulty signals to ensure that the generated samples maintain physical consistency. The integration of the Auxiliary Classifier into the discriminator architecture provides class-conditional information, ensuring that the generated faults belong to specific categories. This is particularly important in mechanical systems where the distinction between various fault signatures can be subtle.\n\nTo ensure the high quality of the generated samples, we incorporate several advanced mechanisms. The discriminators $D_X$ and $D_Y$ are responsible for distinguishing between real and synthetic samples in their respective domains, acting as the primary feedback mechanism for the generators. The WGP module replaces the standard binary cross-entropy loss with the Wasserstein distance to stabilize training and provide meaningful gradients even when the distributions are disjoint. This modification is critical for processing vibration signals, which are often sparse and high-dimensional. Finally, an SAE evaluator is employed to pre-process the signals and extract representative features, aiding in the assessment of the generated data's authenticity. The SAE specifically focuses on identifying the most salient features of the vibration signals, such as periodic impulses and frequency modulation, which are indicative of bearing health. The entire system operates in an end-to-end fashion, iteratively refining the generators until the synthetic samples are indistinguishable from real fault signals while preserving the characteristic signatures of the specific bearing conditions. This architecture not only increases the volume of the training data but also improves the diversity of the fault samples, which is essential for building robust diagnostic models and ensuring that the final classifier generalizes well to unseen real-world scenarios.\n\n\\subsection{Generator and Discriminator with Cycle-Consistency}\n\n[414 more lines in file. Use offset=85 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774414732269}}
{"type":"message","id":"b81274d6","parentId":"530b64c8","timestamp":"2026-03-25T04:59:38.272Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"现在我需要修复这个figure环境。我将替换整个“As illustrated in \\begin{figure}...\\end{figure},”部分，把它变成独立的`figure*`环境。让我找出确切的文本。我将从“As illustrated in”开始，到“\\end{figure},”结束。但要注意，在“\\end{figure}”后面有一个逗号。我将用独立的figure*环境和文本替换。让我写一个edit操作。首先，获取从“As illustrated in”到“\\end{figure},”的精确文本。看起来是这样的：\n\n\"As illustrated in \\\\begin{figure}\\n\\\\centering\\n\\\\includegraphics[width=\\\\columnwidth]{fig2.png}\\n\\\\caption{Figure Architecture}\\n\\\\label{fig:architecture}\\n\\\\end{figure}, the system consists...\"\n\n我将用以下内容替换：\n\n\"\\\\begin{figure*}[htbp]\\n\\\\centering\\n\\\\includegraphics[width=\\\\columnwidth]{fig2.png}\\n\\\\caption{Figure Architecture}\\n\\\\label{fig:architecture}\\n\\\\end{figure*}\\n\\nThe overall architecture of the CAC-CycleGAN-WGP framework...\"\n\n但我需要确保不重复文本。实际上，我需要将整个句子“As illustrated in ... the system consists”分成两部分。让我构造旧字符串和新字符串。\n\n旧字符串：\n\"As illustrated in \\begin{figure}\\n\\centering\\n\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{fig2.png}\\n\\caption{Figure Architecture}\\n\\label{fig:architecture}\\n\\end{figure}, the system consists of five primary components: two generators ($G$ and $F$), two discriminators ($D_X$ and $D_Y$), an Auxiliary Classifier (AC), the Wasserstein Gradient Penalty (WGP) module, and a Sparse Autoencoder (SAE) based evaluator.\"\n\n但旧字符串可能包括段落开头的“The overall architecture...”部分。让我再往前看一点。实际的旧段落从“The overall architecture...”开始。我将替换从“As illustrated in”到“\\end{figure},”的部分。让我开始编辑。首先，使用更精确的旧文本。我将复制确切的文本。让我用grep获取行号。先获取行号，然后提取文本。但也许我可以直接用旧文本：从“As illustrated in”到“\\end{figure},”。让我尝试一下。","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"019d235cb2ee0328b9edc71d0d12e233","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-6/final/v3/paper.tex","oldText":"As illustrated in \\begin{figure}\n\\centering\n\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{fig2.png}\n\\caption{Figure Architecture}\n\\label{fig:architecture}\n\\end{figure}, the system consists of five primary components: two generators ($G$ and $F$), two discriminators ($D_X$ and $D_Y$), an Auxiliary Classifier (AC), the Wasserstein Gradient Penalty (WGP) module, and a Sparse Autoencoder (SAE) based evaluator.","newText":"\\begin{figure*}[htbp]\n\\centering\n\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{fig2.png}\n\\caption{Figure Architecture}\n\\label{fig:architecture}\n\\end{figure*}\n\nThe overall architecture of the CAC-CycleGAN-WGP framework is meticulously designed to transform imbalanced raw vibration signals into a balanced dataset by generating high-fidelity synthetic fault samples. As illustrated in Fig.~\\ref{fig:architecture}, the system consists of five primary components: two generators ($G$ and $F$), two discriminators ($D_X$ and $D_Y$), an Auxiliary Classifier (AC), the Wasserstein Gradient Penalty (WGP) module, and a Sparse Autoencoder (SAE) based evaluator."}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.2","usage":{"input":112349,"output":1463,"cacheRead":32192,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":146004,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774414732274}}
{"type":"message","id":"e977c3ed","parentId":"b81274d6","timestamp":"2026-03-25T04:59:38.281Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"019d235cb2ee0328b9edc71d0d12e233","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in /home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-6/final/v3/paper.tex."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n  69 \n  70 \\subsection{Overall Framework Architecture}\n  71 \\label{subsec:framework}\n  72 \n- 73 The overall architecture of the CAC-CycleGAN-WGP framework is meticulously designed to transform imbalanced raw vibration signals into a balanced dataset by generating high-fidelity synthetic fault samples. As illustrated in \\begin{figure}\n+ 73 The overall architecture of the CAC-CycleGAN-WGP framework is meticulously designed to transform imbalanced raw vibration signals into a balanced dataset by generating high-fidelity synthetic fault samples. \\begin{figure*}[htbp]\n  74 \\centering\n  75 \\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{fig2.png}\n  76 \\caption{Figure Architecture}\n  77 \\label{fig:architecture}\n- 78 \\end{figure}, the system consists of five primary components: two generators ($G$ and $F$), two discriminators ($D_X$ and $D_Y$), an Auxiliary Classifier (AC), the Wasserstein Gradient Penalty (WGP) module, and a Sparse Autoencoder (SAE) based evaluator. This multi-component assembly ensures that the model can handle the complexities of different fault types, such as inner race, outer race, and ball defects, which often exhibit overlapping signal features in the time-frequency domain. In this context, we leverage the CycleGAN \\cite{4} framework for domain-to-domain mapping, combined with the stable training advantages of WGAN-GP \\cite{3} and the categorical guidance of ACGAN \\cite{5}.\n+ 78 \\end{figure*}\n  79 \n+ 80 The overall architecture of the CAC-CycleGAN-WGP framework is meticulously designed to transform imbalanced raw vibration signals into a balanced dataset by generating high-fidelity synthetic fault samples. As illustrated in Fig.~\\ref{fig:architecture}, the system consists of five primary components: two generators ($G$ and $F$), two discriminators ($D_X$ and $D_Y$), an Auxiliary Classifier (AC), the Wasserstein Gradient Penalty (WGP) module, and a Sparse Autoencoder (SAE) based evaluator. This multi-component assembly ensures that the model can handle the complexities of different fault types, such as inner race, outer race, and ball defects, which often exhibit overlapping signal features in the time-frequency domain. In this context, we leverage the CycleGAN \\cite{4} framework for domain-to-domain mapping, combined with the stable training advantages of WGAN-GP \\cite{3} and the categorical guidance of ACGAN \\cite{5}.\n+ 81 \n  80 The workflow begins with the input of raw vibration signals from both the majority class (normally functioning bearings) and the minority class (faulty bearings). Unlike standard GANs that map from a latent noise space to the data distribution—often resulting in a lack of structural coherence—our framework utilizes the CycleGAN structure to perform domain-to-domain translation. Generator $G$ is tasked with mapping samples from the normal domain $X$ to the fault domain $Y$, while generator $F$ performs the inverse mapping. This approach leverages the underlying structural similarities between normal and faulty signals to ensure that the generated samples maintain physical consistency. The integration of the Auxiliary Classifier into the discriminator architecture provides class-conditional information, ensuring that the generated faults belong to specific categories. This is particularly important in mechanical systems where the distinction between various fault signatures can be subtle.\n  81 \n  82 To ensure the high quality of the generated samples, we incorporate several advanced mechanisms. The discriminators $D_X$ and $D_Y$ are responsible for distinguishing between real and synthetic samples in their respective domains, acting as the primary feedback mechanism for the generators. The WGP module replaces the standard binary cross-entropy loss with the Wasserstein distance to stabilize training and provide meaningful gradients even when the distributions are disjoint. This modification is critical for processing vibration signals, which are often sparse and high-dimensional. Finally, an SAE evaluator is employed to pre-process the signals and extract representative features, aiding in the assessment of the generated data's authenticity. The SAE specifically focuses on identifying the most salient features of the vibration signals, such as periodic impulses and frequency modulation, which are indicative of bearing health. The entire system operates in an end-to-end fashion, iteratively refining the generators until the synthetic samples are indistinguishable from real fault signals while preserving the characteristic signatures of the specific bearing conditions. This architecture not only increases the volume of the training data but also improves the diversity of the fault samples, which is essential for building robust diagnostic models and ensuring that the final classifier generalizes well to unseen real-world scenarios.\n  83 \n     ...","firstChangedLine":73},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774414778278}}
{"type":"message","id":"74ca0c1e","parentId":"e977c3ed","timestamp":"2026-03-25T04:59:59.977Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"很好！但请注意，我添加了“The overall architecture of the CAC-CycleGAN-WGP framework...”这一行，而这一行之前可能已经存在。我需要检查一下，是否因为重复导致句子重复。让我查看替换后的文本。不过我可以之后检查。现在修复fig3的环境。让我找到fig3的figure环境。","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"019d235d1a6f0fbb8d0c40cc4d486740","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-6/final/v3/paper.tex","limit":15,"offset":155}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v3.2","usage":{"input":109906,"output":280,"cacheRead":32384,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":142570,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774414778281}}
{"type":"message","id":"4a2ba95c","parentId":"74ca0c1e","timestamp":"2026-03-25T04:59:59.984Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"019d235d1a6f0fbb8d0c40cc4d486740","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\\label{sec:sae}\n\nIn the proposed framework, ensuring the physical consistency and diagnostic utility of the generated data is paramount. Traditional GAN evaluation metrics like the Inception Score (IS) or Frechet Inception Distance (FID) often fail to capture the subtle temporal and spectral nuances of industrial sensor signals, as they were originally designed for natural image datasets. Therefore, we employ a Stacked Autoencoder (SAE) as a dedicated quality evaluator to quantify the fidelity of the synthetic signals relative to the source domain distribution. Sparse Autoencoders, initially popularized by Ng \\cite{Ng2011}, are uniquely suited for this role due to their ability to reconstruct complex signal manifolds through a hierarchical feature extraction process, frequently analyzed using t-SNE \\cite{Maaten2008} for distribution verification.\n\nThe SAE architecture, illustrated in \\begin{figure}\n\\centering\n\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{fig3.png}\n\\caption{Figure Sae}\n\\label{fig:sae}\n\\end{figure}, consists of multiple layers of sparse autoencoders stacked to form a deep representation learner. Each layer is pre-trained to minimize the reconstruction error of its input, progressively extracting high-level abstract features from the raw time-series or frequency-domain data. The encoding stage compresses the input into a latent bottleneck, while the decoding stage attempts to recreate the original signal from this reduced representation. During the evaluation phase, the SAE is trained exclusively on the real data from the target domain $Y$. The fundamental assumption is that if the generator $G$ successfully captures the underlying distribution of domain $Y$, the generated samples $\\tilde{y}$ should yield a reconstruction error comparable to that of real samples.\n\nThe quality of a generated sample $\\tilde{y}$ is assessed using the Reconstruction Error Index (REI), defined as:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\text{REI}(\\tilde{y}) = \\| \\tilde{y} - \\text{SAE}(\\tilde{y}) \\|_2^2\n\\label{eq:rei}\n\n[331 more lines in file. Use offset=170 to continue.]"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774414799979}}
