{"type":"message","id":"6c6555fc","parentId":"7a98532d","timestamp":"2026-03-25T06:38:11.395Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"e9ee892c-af51-4e11-87ee-ee72dcc9b3c9\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"gateway-client\",\n  \"sender\": \"openclaw-tui\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-tui (gateway-client)\",\n  \"id\": \"gateway-client\",\n  \"name\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"username\": \"openclaw-tui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Wed 2026-03-25 14:38 GMT+8] v4用户审查结果如下：major revise. 以下意见：1.figire1-3 并没有正确插入，应该是代码有误，编译后的PDF没有显示。2.referecne 数目太少，至少需要45条"}],"timestamp":1774420691391}}
{"type":"message","id":"7271c4c2","parentId":"6c6555fc","timestamp":"2026-03-25T06:38:28.303Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"用户给出了一个新Reject (v4审查结果，但实际是v3后的版本)。问题：\n1. Figure1-3 没有正确插入，PDF没有显示\n2. 引用数量太少，需要45条\n\n我需要修复这些问题。这应该是指v3/v4版本。让我检查当前final/v3中的figure引用情况，然后添加更多引用到references.bib。\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"收到用户 v4 审查结果（Major Revise）：\n\n1. ❌ Figure1-3 没有正确显示\n2. ❌ 引用数量太少（需45条，当前35条）\n\n开始修复：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_997120f43a774004ba8d05dd","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# 检查 figure1-3 的引用\ngrep -n \"fig1\\|fig2\\|fig3\\|fig:overview\\|fig:architecture\\|fig:sae\" /home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/shared/paper-project-6/final/v3/paper.tex | head -10"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"minimax/minimax-m2.5","usage":{"input":153048,"output":282,"cacheRead":272,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":153602,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774420691394}}
{"type":"message","id":"dab6ca87","parentId":"7271c4c2","timestamp":"2026-03-25T06:38:28.316Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_997120f43a774004ba8d05dd","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"75:The overall architecture of the CAC-CycleGAN-WGP framework is meticulously designed to transform imbalanced raw vibration signals into a balanced dataset by generating high-fidelity synthetic fault samples. As illustrated in  Fig.~\\ref{fig:architecture}, the system consists of five primary components: two generators ($G$ and $F$), two discriminators ($D_X$ and $D_Y$), an Auxiliary Classifier (AC), the Wasserstein Gradient Penalty (WGP) module, and a Sparse Autoencoder (SAE) based evaluator. This multi-component assembly ensures that the model can handle the complexities of different fault types, such as inner race, outer race, and ball defects, which often exhibit overlapping signal features in the time-frequency domain. In this context, we leverage the CycleGAN \\cite{4} framework for domain-to-domain mapping, combined with the stable training advantages of WGAN-GP \\cite{3} and the categorical guidance of ACGAN \\cite{5}.\n154:The SAE architecture, illustrated in  Fig.~\\ref{fig:sae}, consists of multiple layers of sparse autoencoders stacked to form a deep representation learner. Each layer is pre-trained to minimize the reconstruction error of its input, progressively extracting high-level abstract features from the raw time-series or frequency-domain data. The encoding stage compresses the input into a latent bottleneck, while the decoding stage attempts to recreate the original signal from this reduced representation. During the evaluation phase, the SAE is trained exclusively on the real data from the target domain $Y$. The fundamental assumption is that if the generator $G$ successfully captures the underlying distribution of domain $Y$, the generated samples $\\tilde{y}$ should yield a reconstruction error comparable to that of real samples.\n217:\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{combined_fig1.png}\n235:\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{combined_fig3.png}\n294:Furthermore, we evaluate the robustness of the Sparse Autoencoder (SAE) feature extractor used in our diagnostic pipeline against external environmental noise.  Fig.~\\ref{fig:sae_error} tracks the SAE reconstruction error variation across different noisy environments where the Signal-to-Noise Ratio (SNR) varies from -5dB to 20dB. The proposed model exhibits lower sensitivity to Gaussian noise injected into the input signals compared to traditional deep learning models. This is likely because the generative augmentation process itself acts as a form of data-centric regularization, teaching the model to ignore non-essential fluctuations and focus on the core structural components of the fault signal that are invariant to noise.\n330:\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{fig2.png}\n332:\\label{fig:architecture}\n337:\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{fig3.png}\n339:\\label{fig:sae}\n427:\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{combined_fig2.png}"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":6,"aggregated":"75:The overall architecture of the CAC-CycleGAN-WGP framework is meticulously designed to transform imbalanced raw vibration signals into a balanced dataset by generating high-fidelity synthetic fault samples. As illustrated in  Fig.~\\ref{fig:architecture}, the system consists of five primary components: two generators ($G$ and $F$), two discriminators ($D_X$ and $D_Y$), an Auxiliary Classifier (AC), the Wasserstein Gradient Penalty (WGP) module, and a Sparse Autoencoder (SAE) based evaluator. This multi-component assembly ensures that the model can handle the complexities of different fault types, such as inner race, outer race, and ball defects, which often exhibit overlapping signal features in the time-frequency domain. In this context, we leverage the CycleGAN \\cite{4} framework for domain-to-domain mapping, combined with the stable training advantages of WGAN-GP \\cite{3} and the categorical guidance of ACGAN \\cite{5}.\n154:The SAE architecture, illustrated in  Fig.~\\ref{fig:sae}, consists of multiple layers of sparse autoencoders stacked to form a deep representation learner. Each layer is pre-trained to minimize the reconstruction error of its input, progressively extracting high-level abstract features from the raw time-series or frequency-domain data. The encoding stage compresses the input into a latent bottleneck, while the decoding stage attempts to recreate the original signal from this reduced representation. During the evaluation phase, the SAE is trained exclusively on the real data from the target domain $Y$. The fundamental assumption is that if the generator $G$ successfully captures the underlying distribution of domain $Y$, the generated samples $\\tilde{y}$ should yield a reconstruction error comparable to that of real samples.\n217:\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{combined_fig1.png}\n235:\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{combined_fig3.png}\n294:Furthermore, we evaluate the robustness of the Sparse Autoencoder (SAE) feature extractor used in our diagnostic pipeline against external environmental noise.  Fig.~\\ref{fig:sae_error} tracks the SAE reconstruction error variation across different noisy environments where the Signal-to-Noise Ratio (SNR) varies from -5dB to 20dB. The proposed model exhibits lower sensitivity to Gaussian noise injected into the input signals compared to traditional deep learning models. This is likely because the generative augmentation process itself acts as a form of data-centric regularization, teaching the model to ignore non-essential fluctuations and focus on the core structural components of the fault signal that are invariant to noise.\n330:\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{fig2.png}\n332:\\label{fig:architecture}\n337:\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{fig3.png}\n339:\\label{fig:sae}\n427:\\includegraphics[width=\\columnwidth]{combined_fig2.png}","cwd":"/home/liaowenjie/.openclaw-multi/leader/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774420708311}}
